Phase 5 — Architecture Planning
Goal: Choose and fully justify the technical architecture.

5.1 Architecture Pattern
State the chosen pattern and justify it against the app's specific requirements.

Default recommendation for most Android apps: MVVM + Clean Architecture

Justify against these criteria:

Testability (unit, integration, UI)
Separation of concerns
Lifecycle awareness
Google/JetBrains official guidance alignment
Team/AI agent maintainability
5.2 Layer Definitions
Presentation Layer
  └─ Composables / Fragments / Activities
  └─ ViewModels (expose StateFlow / UiState sealed class)
  └─ UI Events (user actions → ViewModel)
Domain Layer (optional but recommended for complex apps)
  └─ Use Cases (one public method: operator fun invoke())
  └─ Domain Models (pure Kotlin data classes, no Android imports)
  └─ Repository Interfaces (contracts, not implementations)
Data Layer
  └─ Repository Implementations
  └─ Local Data Source (Room DAOs)
  └─ Remote Data Source (Retrofit service interfaces)
  └─ Data Transfer Objects (DTOs)
  └─ Mappers (DTO ↔ Domain Model)

5.3 State Management
UI State pattern:
  sealed class [ScreenName]UiState {
      object Loading : [ScreenName]UiState()
      data class Success(val data: [DataType]) : [ScreenName]UiState()
      data class Error(val message: String) : [ScreenName]UiState()
      object Empty : [ScreenName]UiState()
  }

Specify which StateFlow / SharedFlow / Channel to use for each concern:

UI state → StateFlow<UiState>
One-shot events (navigation, snackbar) → Channel<UiEvent> consumed as Flow
Reactive data streams → Flow<T> from Room / DataStore
5.4 Dependency Injection Strategy
Framework: Hilt (default) or Koin (justify if chosen)
Scope mapping: Singleton / ActivityRetained / ViewModel / Fragment
5.5 Async & Threading Strategy
Coroutines + Flow/StateFlow for all async work
Dispatcher mapping:
Dispatchers.IO — network, disk
Dispatchers.Default — CPU-intensive (audio processing, image manipulation)
Dispatchers.Main — UI updates only
WorkManager for deferrable background tasks
5.6 Error Handling Strategy
Sealed Result wrapper pattern:
  sealed class Result<out T> {
      data class Success<T>(val data: T) : Result<T>()
      data class Error(val exception: Throwable, val message: String) : Result<Nothing>()
      object Loading : Result<Nothing>()
  }

Every repository method returns Flow<Result<T>>. ViewModels map to UiState. Never swallow exceptions silently.

5.7 Offline Strategy
State explicitly:

Offline-first: Room is source of truth, network syncs in background
Online-only: show error UI, disable actions, retry mechanism
Hybrid: specify which features work offline vs. which require network
Validation Checkpoint ✓
 Architecture choice is justified against this app's specific requirements
 Every layer has a documented responsibility boundary
 UiState sealed class structure is defined for every screen
 Error handling strategy covers network errors, DB errors, and unexpected exceptions
Phase 6 — Data Flow
Goal: Trace how data moves end-to-end for every major user action.

For each core feature, produce a flow diagram:

[User Action]
    ↓
[Composable / Fragment] — emits UiEvent
    ↓
[ViewModel] — calls Use Case / Repository
    ↓
[Use Case] — applies business logic (if domain layer exists)
    ↓
[Repository Interface]
    ↓
[Data Source Decision]
    ├─ Local (Room) → always read cache first
    └─ Remote (Retrofit) → fetch if cache stale or missing
    ↓
[Mapper] — DTO → Domain Model
    ↓
[Repository] — emits Flow<Result<T>>
    ↓
[ViewModel] — maps Result<T> → UiState
    ↓
[Composable / Fragment] — renders UiState

Document the Loading → Success / Error transitions explicitly for each flow.

Document the optimistic update vs. pessimistic update decision for write operations:

Optimistic: Update UI immediately, roll back on error (better UX for reliable networks)
Pessimistic: Wait for server confirmation before updating UI (safer for financial/critical data)
Validation Checkpoint ✓
