Phase 7 — Database & Local Storage Design
Goal: Design every local data structure before a line of Room code is written.

7.1 Do We Need a Database?
State explicitly. If no persistent structured data exists, skip to Phase 10.

7.2 Database Choice & Justification
Default: Room (SQLite abstraction, official Jetpack, observable with Flow)

Justify any deviation (e.g., Realm for complex object graphs, SQLDelight for KMP).

7.3 Entity Definitions
For every table:

Entity: [TableName]
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Column          Type        Constraints       Notes
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
id              Long        PK, autoGenerate  Stable row identity
[field]         [type]      [NOT NULL/UNIQUE]  [business meaning]
createdAt       Long        NOT NULL          Unix timestamp (ms)
updatedAt       Long        NOT NULL          Unix timestamp (ms)
isDeleted       Boolean     DEFAULT false     Soft delete support

Always include createdAt, updatedAt, and isDeleted (soft delete) on every entity unless there is an explicit reason not to.

7.4 Relationships & Indices
Relationship: [EntityA] → [EntityB]
Type: One-to-Many / Many-to-Many / One-to-One
Foreign Key: [EntityB].parentId → [EntityA].id
On Delete: CASCADE / SET NULL / RESTRICT (justify choice)
Index: CREATE INDEX ON [EntityB](parentId) [reason: frequent join query]

7.5 DAO Design Principles
Every DAO method that returns data returns Flow<T> (reactive, not suspend)
Every DAO method that writes data is suspend fun
No business logic inside DAOs — logic belongs in repositories or use cases
7.6 Migration Strategy
Room migration objects for every schema version change
Fallback: fallbackToDestructiveMigration() only in debug builds, never production
Document which version introduces which table/column changes
7.7 Preferences / Settings Storage
DataStore (Proto or Preferences) — never SharedPreferences for new code
List every key, its type, default value, and which component reads/writes it
Sensitive preferences (tokens, keys) → EncryptedSharedPreferences or Keystore
Validation Checkpoint ✓
 Every entity has a primary key, createdAt, updatedAt, and isDeleted
 Every relationship has a defined ON DELETE behavior
 No SharedPreferences usage — DataStore only
 Migration strategy accounts for every schema change
